##Diary of a woman living alone in a walled city of Wuhan | January 23 -- 26

Micro signal

Features an introduction to the refreshing flavor of the feminist hardcore

This is my friend Guo Jing's diary.

This paper records the real life experience and psychological feelings of the foreign women who lived alone in Wuhan during the period of Fengcheng.
Her first post on Weibo was retweeted nearly 5,000 times, while the second was severely restricted. So I want to help her edit and reprint it on wechat.
Some friends suggested that Guo Jing could study or do some work during this time, but obviously this is not very realistic.
It had taken almost all her strength to maintain her daily life and her physical and mental health. But she kept a diary and sent it anyway.
These personal experiences and feelings are an attempt to keep us connected during this period and are a precious historical record.
Welcome to Follow@guo Jing, a social worker on Weibo

In this war, most individuals are on their own, with no system to protect them. I'm relatively young, and it's hard to imagine how more vulnerable individuals, like older people living alone or people with disabilities, can win this battle.

View from a window after the closure of the city (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

January 23rd

I am a calm and calm person, until January 20, Wuhan more than 100 new cases, cases in other provinces and cities, I began to feel at a loss. It is clear that there was a cover-up in the earlier announcements. Also from that day on, there was a sudden increase in the number of people wearing masks on the streets of Wuhan. Many pharmacies sold out of medical masks, and many people bought medicines to prevent and treat colds. I had a cold at the time, and although I was almost cured, I was standing in line to buy a mask when I saw the person in front of me buy four boxes of Oseltamivir. I also bought one box, 62 boxes, which is still a bit expensive.

These days I have been in anxiety, from the local news updates, most of the confirmed cases were in Wuhan 15 days ago. Wuhan has the largest number of university students in the world, and the middle of January is the time for university holidays. Now is also the Spring Festival, the station traffic is bound to be very large. However, Wuhan Railway Station is not strictly regulated. I don't go home for the Spring Festival. It's safest to stay where I am. When I woke up this morning, I was at a loss as to what it would mean, how long it would last, and what preparations to make.

In recent days, we have seen a lot of angry news: Many patients have not been admitted to the hospital after being diagnosed; many patients with fever can not be treated; and W SHU J and People's Congress Ren Chaoliang of Hubei Province, vice Secretary J of the provincial Party Committee, Governor Wang Xiaodong and other leaders on January 21 watched the Spring Festival visit of Hubei Province literary performance..

A corner of the supermarket (picture provided by Guo Jing)

My friends told me to stock up, I did not want to go out, see x is still in the order to order first, but worried about delivery will stop at any time. I also hold to see outside the mood out the door, outside are basically middle-aged and old people, young people less. To the nearby supermarket, many people are in the queue checkout, rice and noodles these survival food has been left few, in a panic I took some randomly. A man sold a lot of salt, some people say you buy so much salt, he said that in case of a year.

Didn't think much of it on the way out, no backpacks, no suitcases, not much to carry. I went out a second time, and began to realize the despair of joy I had just "snatched" , and I began to feel terrible. Seeing some old people on the road who are not strong, they are more difficult under such circumstances. Later I thought there would still be supplies of daily necessities even if the city was closed, so I bought some "luxuries" like yogurt and honey on my second trip.

People line up at a pharmacy (photo courtesy of Guo Jing)

I stopped by the pharmacy on the way home, and it's starting to control people. There were no masks or alcohol in the pharmacy, cold medicine was on sale, and when I tried to leave, no one would come in. A middle aged woman stopped me and asked me to buy her alcohol. Her voice was full of eagerness, like a plea for help.

After stocking up on food, I was still in shock. There are fewer and fewer cars and people on the road today, and a city comes to a halt. When will it come back to life?

Elderly people outside the supermarket (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

24 January

The world is eerily quiet.

I live alone, and it's only when I hear voices in the hallway that I know someone else is there.

I had a lot of time to think about how I was GONNA survive. I don't have the resources or the contacts in the system, and if I get sick, I'm just as untreatable as a lot of other people. So one of my goals is to try not to get sick, and I'm going to keep exercising. I needed food to survive, so I needed to know how much I needed.

At present, the government did not say how long to seal off the city, nor tell us how to ensure the city's operation after the closure. Some have predicted that the city could be closed until May, based on the number of people currently interfering. In order to survive, I had to know what was around where I lived, not live in The Truman Show. So, I went out today. The drugstore and convenience store downstairs were closed. I Walk to the nearby supermarket, which is less than a kilometer away, and I find some comfort in the fact that the x's delivery man is still delivering food.

Streets in Wuhan (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

There are still a lot of people buying in the supermarket. The noodles are almost gone. There are still some rice left. I figured since I was here, I'd buy something, something vegetable that needed to be weighed, and there were 20 or 30 people in the line to be weighed, so I just bought some sausages, meals, dumplings, and meat. Next thing I know, I'm at the drugstore, and there's still no mask or alcohol. I got vitamin C effervescent tablets and iodine. I had little stock of medication at home, and since I rarely got sick, I decided to stick to vitamin C effervescent tablets for the time being. (netizens leave a message saying don't eat VC effervescent tablets every day)

Vegetable racks in supermarkets (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

I saw a lot of people wearing double masks when I was waiting in the checkout line and decided to follow suit. The couple in front were talking about what else to buy. They bought disposable medical gloves and said they could wear them when they went out. I bought one as soon as I could. Later, medical masks arrived, a bag of 100, I had taken two bags, a guide said a bag to 198, I quietly put back a bag. When I found a bag of 99 at the checkout, I regretted it again. But I also gained the confidence to live a little longer. Scarcity makes people feel insecure, especially in these extreme conditions of survival.

I went to the market again, the stall was half empty, and there were fewer vegetables to sell. I bought celery, garlic moss and eggs. A few scattered shops were open, and the spicy beef noodle shop said it would be closed today. I didn't ask at the wreath shop. They seem to be watching a documentary about SARS. I was surprised to see a flower shop that was still open. Next time it was open, I bought a potted plant.

Flower Shop (photo courtesy of Guo Jing)

When I got home, I washed all my clothes and took a bath. It's important to keep clean now. About 20,30 times a day. When the half day was over, I began to make lunch. Going out made me feel connected to the world, and I learned a few survival tips from others.

In this war, most individuals are on their own, with no system to protect them. I'm relatively young, and it's hard to imagine how more vulnerable individuals, like older people living alone or people with disabilities, can win this battle.

A corner of the supermarket (picture provided by Guo Jing)

Guo Jing's message on Weibo

25 January

The weather in Wuhan is as gloomy as it is in Wuhan today. Yesterday was New Year's Eve. Today is Spring Festival. I have never had much interest in festivals, and now they are even more irrelevant to me. Yesterday, I posted my experiences and feelings in the past two days, which got a lot of attention unexpectedly. This focus became my connection to the world.

When Lu suggested I write about my experiences in Wuhan, I hesitated a little. There are many reasons why I don't want to be treated as a totally miserable victim and give the impression that she's miserable. I moved to Wuhan in November of 19, many people do not know, I do not want to deal with a lot of greetings, may be offered to help, I do not want to bring trouble to others. I don't feel comfortable getting attention, and frankly I'm not the worst, there are more sick people who need real attention. Perhaps more fundamentally, I was unwilling to admit that I was miserable, that it took courage to admit that I was weak.

As an advocate for gender equality, I know better than anyone that to solve a social problem, someone has to speak up. I decided to try to keep track because I really need support right now. I got a lot of help from making my records public, including practical life skills like not taking effervescent tablets every day, being careful about how you take your masks and gloves, not taking Oseltamivir; and touching and spiritual healing, some people said they wanted to send me salted duck from Nanjing, not that kind of salted duck bought at the supermarket, nor the so-called famous-brand salted duck, but that kind of salted duck which is usually bought in line at the pickle shop. Ordinary people feel that it is especially delicious and can be vacuum packed, i've been told to put on lip balm, sent masks, alcohol, and received money from friends.

New Year's Eve dinner (picture provided by Guo Jing)

These two days when cooking I have started to control the amount of food, each meal is half the usual amount of stir-fry, I hope not so fast to eat only pickles life. On New Year's Eve, my dinner was 300 grams of dumplings filled with corn, vegetables and pork and five braised chicken wings. Of course, there was no reduction last night.

When we were having dinner, we had a video chat with some friends. We couldn't escape the topic of pneumonia. In fact, people all over the world were more or less affected. Some friends were in the prefecture-level city of Wuhan, and some friends from different places decided not to go home because of pneumonia, friends who "risk their lives" to get together. Fortunately, our conversation was not dominated by pneumonia, and we could make fun of it when we talked about it. A friend coughed during the video, and someone joked, please exit the video.

In a dig at Heterosexuality, we began to play a game called "36 questions to make a stranger fall in love quickly. ". The first question is "who would you like to have dinner with if you could have anyone in the world? " Two friends said. I was a little embarrassed, and of course they meant it, especially now that I don't know how long I'll be stuck in a city. I interjected that the question should be asking people to name their idols, their stars, their sexual fantasies. As it turned out, everyone had a different answer, and someone chose Zhong Nanshan.

Yaohua noodles open but not open (picture provided by Guo Jing)

Maybe the problem isn't so interesting, and we'll be out of the game soon. I don't know what to talk about, but some people said they were confused about some topics recently and wanted to discuss them with others. So we got down to serious business, including why everyone was attacking Wu Xin personally and how women in intimate relationships were perceived as weak.

My fellow feminists have always looked at a woman's environment, not just what someone says or does. It's always easier to go after the individual, but we're in a social structure. My present sense of despair can not be attributed to any particular individual, but to a disappointment in the rotten institution and structure. The government is the one with the resources and the power to do something, and the opposite is true.

Later, a friend's family ordered Barbecue take-out, watching them in front of me without restraint to eat barbecue good happiness. And I'm glad they're not avoiding me, because it's totally unnecessary. It's important for everyone to lead their own lives.

Indescribable Wreath Shop (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

We talked for, like, three hours past 11:00. I felt happy for a moment and thought I could go to sleep with this satisfaction. I didn't expect to close my eyes. Everything that's happened lately is flashing in my mind. It's all so magical. "Why did this happen to me? " Flashed through my mind, and I quickly put a stop to the thought, because it was a bad omen. If one constantly questioned life, it would only increase one's sense of powerlessness.

I know it's hard, but "how" is more important. The thought thought thought, the tears flowed out involuntarily. These tears mixed feelings, there is powerlessness, anger, touched, sad... I also think of death, in fact, there is not too much regret, because I have been doing what I think valuable work.

The luckiest thing in life is to be a feminist and work with a group of like minded people who support and keep each other company. And I still don't want it to end. So my mind again came up with what to do after unsealing, I imagine that is what kind of joy, through this hurdle, my life is another level up. I quickly interrupted the thought, after all, it had been only two days. I don't know how long I thought about it, but I finally went to sleep.

Sports Punch card (picture provided by Guo Jing)

Wake up at 7:00 in the morning, do not want to get up, stay up for a while and can not sleep or get up. Hypochondria may be the biggest psychological disorder now. When I blew my nose this morning, I was shocked to see blood. The thought of getting sick after you throw away the tissue is still in your mind.

I went to Tongji Hospital for an eye exam on December 30, and went to Guilin on January 9, when a friend had a cold, and I caught a cold. I went back to Wuhan on January 13, and I didn't take my medicine, but the cold is definitely getting better. After that, a friend stayed with me for a few days, and I met a few friends. They're fine so far.

And then I wonder if I shouldn't go out. But I do not have a fever, I have a strong appetite, I want to eat hot pot with friends. I couldn't let myself get caught up in the vortex of Hypochondria. I opened the Keep and started exercising. After exercising I went out.

A shop with chrysanthemums (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

It's still pretty bleak out there. Today, I wore a double mask, even though many people said it was useless and unnecessary. I am afraid that if there are fake and inferior products, it can also increase my sense of security. Out of the Elevator Mirror found in the eye excrement, I think it is better not to deal with it, let it go. I saw a cashew noodles opened the door, I was about to enter, the boss put a wave of hands that closed. The wreath shop was still open, and had put some chrysanthemums in front of it. I wonder if it had any special meaning. Five meters away from the wreath shop in an alley with the same chrysanthemum, an old man stood there, a sense of solemnity, I walked past carefully turned his head to take photos.

I went to the same supermarket, the vegetable shelves were almost empty, and there were few dumplings and noodles left. There wasn't a lot of people lined up to be weighed today, so I just bought some sweet potatoes. To The supermarket seems to have to buy some things, in fact, I have saved about 7 kilograms of rice, I still bought 2.5 kilograms of rice, still can not help but buy some dumplings, salted duck eggs, intestines, red beans, Mung beans, millet. I don't really like salted duck eggs. I save them just in case. When it's unsealed, there'll be salted duck eggs left, which I'm giving away. I suddenly thought this was a bit morbid. In fact, I had enough food at home to last me for at least a month. But how could I be so hard on myself in this situation.

I also went to the same pharmacy, asked whether there is alcohol, the guide answered no, and said you did not come yesterday. I said yes, thinking I might come every day.

The florist was still open, and the rest of the plants were not so green. I chose a pot of leaves on some spots of the green radish, because it is easy to raise. I have a pot of sick mint at home, and its leaves are turning yellow. It's my first mint, and I'm not sure what it is, I don't know what to do. Then I went to the market, which was closed today.

A view of the Yangtze River (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

I plan to take a walk by the river today. I drank a little water on the way out the door, I peed in the supermarket, and I was carrying something, and I kind of wanted to give up. But my life is so monotonous. The supermarket is about 500 meters away from the river, I will go to the river from the road next to the supermarket, the road also has 2 small shops open the door, there are people walking the dog. This is a road I have not been through, somehow feel their world was opened a little bit. There are also scattered strollers along the river. They don't want to be trapped, do they.

Going to the supermarket every day is like grasping at the last thing that can be grasped. I can't go to the supermarket every day. I have to have time to relax. When the Sun comes out, I won't go to the supermarket. I'll just walk by the river.

Guo Jing's new pot -- a leaf tree (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

26 January

It's not just cities that are being cordoned off, it's people's voices.

When I tweeted my notes on the first day, the pictures wouldn't go up, and the text wouldn't go out, so I had to turn the text into pictures. Yesterday, I was unable to post on my friends'circle even if I turned my text into a picture, and my Weibo account was apparently blocked after it was posted. Nearly 5,000 people retweeted the post on Jan. 24, compared with 45 yesterday. For a second, I wondered if I was bad at it. Censorship and restrictions on the Internet are not new, but they are more brutal now. Many people in Fengcheng are trapped in their homes, relying on the Internet to get information and keep in touch with family and friends so that we don't have to be an island.

After posting on Weibo on the 24th, I got a call from the director of CCTV news investigation. She said she had seen my Weibo and did not expect me to be in Wuhan. She was doing a show about sexism in employment last year, and she interviewed me because I've been working on it for years. After that, our contact is very little, received her telephone I feel a little surprised and touched. These two days, someone shared with me their current situation, someone sent care and blessing. At first I wasn't sure if I could keep writing every day, but now I've decided to make a commitment that I will keep writing and try to get it out. Maybe there will be a blockade after that, I hope everyone can see my notes to help forward, and remember@me, let me know that someone is watching.

CCTV report on Guo Jing (picture provided by Guo Jing)

Yesterday's dinner was sweet potatoes, Yogurt and fried eggplant. Last night, I video chat with my friends for more than 3 hours, there is a lot of small talk. We talked about "if you could have anyone in the world, who would you like to have dinner with? " The friend who had chosen to have dinner with me the previous day had changed.

Everyone knows it's important to keep exercising, but it's hard to do it alone. A friend who stayed at my house the other day said she could make us practice Ukulele every day when she was at my house, and she didn't do it when she was alone. So we suggested that we do some exercise during the video, and several people actually moved for a while. A friend in Beijing said the city's intercity buses were out of service.

Guangzhou friends have also seen some of the Guangzhou City closed off the grapevine news. They said to make a shopping list (I left it at the end) . We also talked about a lot of volunteer organizations, organizations that donate supplies, organizations that organize information. We were concerned that the identity and perspective of women such as caregivers might be overlooked in pneumonia, so I started a feminist group to discuss and act from a feminist perspective. Discussing what to do with others can help individuals overcome some feelings of powerlessness.

Dinner (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

In Times of great change, it can be a great challenge to re-establish the routine. I Keep doing Keep in the morning. I suddenly realized that I was doing support and alternating shoulder strokes when I was supposed to be doing a side knee lift. I wasn't concentrating on the exercise, my mind was occupied with a lot of things. But building a new routine is about regaining control, and in order to stay healthy, I have to work hard. When I was getting ready to go out, I found that I had forgotten to air yesterday's clothes. I had to get another outfit for the trip.

Out of the community that moment, depression feeling. The shops on both sides were closed. I only see three people -- a sanitation worker, a janitor, and a passerby. I began to count in my mind how many people I would meet today. When I walked to the waist noodle shop 500 meters from my house, I met eight people.

Street view of Wuhan (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

The waist flower shop is still open, the boss is doing take-out. The wreath shop was closed. The old man of yesterday was still standing at the entrance of the Alley, not wearing a mask, looking at the sporadic passers-by.

The supermarket was still open, the shelves for vegetables, noodles and rice were empty, and again today there were many people waiting in line to be weighed. I walked around the supermarket and felt a little proud that I finally stopped shopping today. The florist is out delivering flowers, and the market is still closed.

A corner of the supermarket (picture provided by Guo Jing)

After my daily routine, I suddenly didn't want to go home. I didn't want to be stuck in a certain area. So I decided to take a step forward. Come Wuhan 2 many months, I do not like to go shopping, also do not have many friends in this city, seldom go out. In late December, a friend from out of town took me to Florida, an Internet sensation near my home. I said I'd bring them here if any of my friends came. I saw a sign on the road to Tanhualin, so I followed.

The traffic lights were still on, and when I saw them, I consciously stopped for a moment, and then, realizing that there were no cars on the road at all, I kept going. The sign led me to a village in the city. Walking along the narrow path, listening to my footsteps, I felt as if I knew more about Wuhan. There was an open door with a mourning hall, and I wondered if she had died of pneumonia. Village in the city is always like a maze, do not know where it will go.

Street view of Wuhan (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

I don't know where I went, but I didn't go to Tanhualin. But Tanhualin wasn't supposed to be my destination. After about a kilometer, I turned back. On the way back, the door of the mourning hall closed. On the road four or five of the door are affixed with elegiac couplets, the first time I passed by the time I did not notice.

I haven't been able to accurately count since the supermarket. I must have met hundreds of people today. Home is still washing clothes, bathing, mopping the floor, cooking. After the meal, I was able to catch my breath and a little tired. This is probably the routine of many housewives, and it's amazing how they can do it day in and day out. I was going to sleep, but I didn't, because I wanted to write today's notes. I'M GONNA keep talking, I'm GonNa Break The blockade, and I want you to have hope. My friend, I'd like to see you sometime.

Street view of Wuhan (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Shopping list

Bottom line:

Rice, noodles, pickles, salted duck eggs, etc. 
These are essential and life-saving foods and can be stored for a long time

Basic Life:

Potatoes, carrots, onions, celery, garlic moss, meat, etc. 
These ingredients are used in everyday cooking and are relatively resistant to release

"LUXURY GOODS" :

Dried fish, dried bean curd, dried meat, honey, yogurt and so on
(these foods can help reduce our sense of scarcity and help us feel that there is more to life than just surviving.)

24 January

The world is eerily quiet.

I live alone, and it's only when I hear voices in the hallway that I know someone else is there.

I had a lot of time to think about how I was GONNA survive. I don't have the resources or the contacts in the system, and if I get sick, I'm just as untreatable as a lot of other people. So one of my goals is to try not to get sick, and I'm going to keep exercising. I needed food to survive, so I needed to know how much I needed.

At present, the government did not say how long to seal off the city, nor tell us how to ensure the city's operation after the closure. Some have predicted that the city could be closed until May, based on the number of people currently interfering. In order to survive, I had to know what was around where I lived, not live in The Truman Show. So, I went out today. The drugstore and convenience store downstairs were closed. I Walk to the nearby supermarket, which is less than a kilometer away, and I find some comfort in the fact that the x's delivery man is still delivering food.

There are still a lot of people buying in the supermarket. The noodles are almost gone. There are still some rice left. I saw a lot of people wearing double masks when I was waiting in the checkout line and decided to follow suit. The couple in front were talking about what else to buy. They bought disposable medical gloves and said they could wear them when they went out. I bought one as soon as I could. Later, medical masks arrived, a bag of 100, I had taken two bags, a guide said a bag to 198, I quietly put back a bag. When I found a bag of 99 at the checkout, I regretted it again. But I also gained the confidence to live a little longer. Scarcity makes people feel insecure, especially in these extreme conditions of survival.

I was surprised to see a flower shop that was still open. Next time it was open, I bought a potted plant.

25 January

The weather in Wuhan is as gloomy as it is in Wuhan today. Yesterday was New Year's Eve. Today is Spring Festival. I have never had much interest in festivals, and now they are even more irrelevant to me. Yesterday, I posted my experiences and feelings in the past two days, which got a lot of attention unexpectedly. This focus became my connection to the world.

When Lu suggested I write about my experiences in Wuhan, I hesitated a little. There are many reasons why I don't want to be treated as a totally miserable victim and give the impression that she's miserable. I moved to Wuhan in November of 19, many people do not know, I do not want to deal with a lot of greetings, may be offered to help, I do not want to bring trouble to others. I don't feel comfortable getting attention, and frankly I'm not the worst, there are more sick people who need real attention. Perhaps more fundamentally, I was unwilling to admit that I was miserable, that it took courage to admit that I was weak.

As an advocate for gender equality, I know better than anyone that to solve a social problem, someone has to speak up. I decided to try to keep track because I really need support right now. I got a lot of help from making my records public, including practical life skills like not taking effervescent tablets every day, being careful about how you take your masks and gloves, not taking Oseltamivir; and touching and spiritual healing, some people said they wanted to send me salted duck from Nanjing, not that kind of salted duck bought at the supermarket, nor the so-called famous-brand salted duck, but that kind of salted duck which is usually bought in line at the pickle shop. Ordinary people feel that it is especially delicious and can be vacuum packed, i've been told to put on lip balm, sent masks, alcohol, and received money from friends.

These two days when cooking I have started to control the amount of food, each meal is half the usual amount of stir-fry, I hope not so fast to eat only pickles life. On New Year's Eve, my dinner was 300 grams of dumplings filled with corn, vegetables and pork and five braised chicken wings. Of course, there was no reduction last night.

When we were having dinner, we had a video chat with some friends. We couldn't escape the topic of pneumonia. In fact, people all over the world were more or less affected. Some friends were in the prefecture-level city of Wuhan, and some friends from different places decided not to go home because of pneumonia, friends who "risk their lives" to get together. Fortunately, our conversation was not dominated by pneumonia, and we could make fun of it when we talked about it. A friend coughed during the video, and someone joked, please exit the video.

In a dig at Heterosexuality, we began to play a game called "36 questions to make a stranger fall in love quickly. ". The first question is "who would you like to have dinner with if you could have anyone in the world? " Two friends said. I was a little embarrassed, and of course they meant it, especially now that I don't know how long I'll be stuck in a city. I interjected that the question should be asking people to name their idols, their stars, their sexual fantasies. As it turned out, everyone had a different answer, and someone chose Zhong Nanshan.

Maybe the problem isn't so interesting, and we'll be out of the game soon. I don't know what to talk about, but some people said they were confused about some topics recently and wanted to discuss them with others. So we got down to serious business, including why everyone was attacking Wu Xin personally and how women in intimate relationships were perceived as weak.

My fellow feminists have always looked at a woman's environment, not just what someone says or does. It's always easier to go after the individual, but we're in a social structure. My present sense of despair can not be attributed to any particular individual, but to a disappointment in the rotten institution and structure. The government is the one with the resources and the power to do something, and the opposite is true.

Later, a friend's family ordered Barbecue take-out, watching them in front of me without restraint to eat barbecue good happiness. And I'm glad they're not avoiding me, because it's totally unnecessary. It's important for everyone to lead their own lives.

We talked for, like, three hours past 11:00. I felt happy for a moment and thought I could go to sleep with this satisfaction. I didn't expect to close my eyes. Everything that's happened lately is flashing in my mind. It's all so magical. "Why did this happen to me? " Flashed through my mind, and I quickly put a stop to the thought, because it was a bad omen. If one constantly questioned life, it would only increase one's sense of powerlessness.

I know it's hard, but "how" is more important. The thought thought thought, the tears flowed out involuntarily. These tears mixed feelings, there is powerlessness, anger, touched, sad... I also think of death, in fact, there is not too much regret, because I have been doing what I think valuable work.

The luckiest thing in life is to be a feminist and work with a group of like minded people who support and keep each other company. And I still don't want it to end. So my mind again came up with what to do after unsealing, I imagine that is what kind of joy, through this hurdle, my life is another level up. I quickly interrupted the thought, after all, it had been only two days. I don't know how long I thought about it, but I finally went to sleep.

Wake up at 7:00 in the morning, do not want to get up, stay up for a while and can not sleep or get up. Hypochondria may be the biggest psychological disorder now. When I blew my nose this morning, I was shocked to see blood. The thought of getting sick after you throw away the tissue is still in your mind.

I went to Tongji Hospital for an eye exam on December 30, and went to Guilin on January 9, when a friend had a cold, and I caught a cold. I went back to Wuhan on January 13, and I didn't take my medicine, but the cold is definitely getting better. After that, a friend stayed with me for a few days, and I met a few friends. They're fine so far.

And then I wonder if I shouldn't go out. But I do not have a fever, I have a strong appetite, I want to eat hot pot with friends. I couldn't let myself get caught up in the vortex of Hypochondria. I opened the Keep and started exercising. After exercising I went out.

26 January

It's not just cities that are being cordoned off, it's people's voices.

When I tweeted my notes on the first day, the pictures wouldn't go up, and the text wouldn't go out, so I had to turn the text into pictures. Yesterday, I was unable to post on my friends'circle even if I turned my text into a picture, and my Weibo account was apparently blocked after it was posted. Nearly 5,000 people retweeted the post on Jan. 24, compared with 45 yesterday. For a second, I wondered if I was bad at it. Censorship and restrictions on the Internet are not new, but they are more brutal now. Many people in Fengcheng are trapped in their homes, relying on the Internet to get information and keep in touch with family and friends so that we don't have to be an island.

After posting on Weibo on the 24th, I got a call from the director of CCTV news investigation. She said she had seen my Weibo and did not expect me to be in Wuhan. She was doing a show about sexism in employment last year, and she interviewed me because I've been working on it for years. After that, our contact is very little, received her telephone I feel a little surprised and touched. These two days, someone shared with me their current situation, someone sent care and blessing. At first I wasn't sure if I could keep writing every day, but now I've decided to make a commitment that I will keep writing and try to get it out. Maybe there will be a blockade after that, I hope everyone can see my notes to help forward, and remember@me, let me know that someone is watching.

Street view of Wuhan (image courtesy of Guo Jing)

The waist flower shop is still open, the boss is doing take-out. The wreath shop was closed. The old man of yesterday was still standing at the entrance of the Alley, not wearing a mask, looking at the sporadic passers-by.

The supermarket was still open, the shelves for vegetables, noodles and rice were empty, and again today there were many people waiting in line to be weighed. I walked around the supermarket and felt a little proud that I finally stopped shopping today. The florist is out delivering flowers, and the market is still closed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After my daily routine, I suddenly didn't want to go home. I didn't want to be stuck in a certain area. So I decided to take a step forward. Come Wuhan 2 many months, I do not like to go shopping, also do not have many friends in this city, seldom go out. In late December, a friend from out of town took me to Florida, an Internet sensation near my home. I said I'd bring them here if any of my friends came. I saw a sign on the road to Tanhualin, so I followed.

The traffic lights were still on, and when I saw them, I consciously stopped for a moment, and then, realizing that there were no cars on the road at all, I kept going. The sign led me to a village in the city. Walking along the narrow path, listening to my footsteps, I felt as if I knew more about Wuhan. There was an open door with a mourning hall, and I wondered if she had died of pneumonia. Village in the city is always like a maze, do not know where it will go.

On the way back, the door of the mourning hall closed. On the road four or five of the door are affixed with elegiac couplets, the first time I passed by the time I did not notice.

I haven't been able to accurately count since the supermarket. I must have met hundreds of people today. Home is still washing clothes, bathing, mopping the floor, cooking. After the meal, I was able to catch my breath and a little tired. This is probably the routine of many housewives, and it's amazing how they can do it day in and day out. I was going to sleep, but I didn't, because I wanted to write today's notes. I'M GONNA keep talking, I'm GonNa Break The blockade, and I want you to have hope. Shopping list

Bottom line:

Rice, noodles, pickles, salted duck eggs, etc. 
These are essential and life-saving foods and can be stored for a long time

Basic Life:

Potatoes, carrots, onions, celery, garlic moss, meat, etc. 
These ingredients are used in everyday cooking and are relatively resistant to release

"LUXURY GOODS" :

Dried fish, dried bean curd, dried meat, honey, yogurt and so on
(these foods can help reduce our sense of scarcity and help us feel that there is more to life than just surviving.)
